---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { articleSchema, faqSchema } from '../../../../data/schema.js';
import { topics } from '../../../../data/ages.js';

const title = '6–9 Month Old Sleep: What to Expect and Is It Normal?';
const description = 'Between 6 and 9 months, many babies begin sleeping through the night, but developmental leaps like crawling and separation anxiety can trigger regressions. Learn about 6-9 month sleep patterns, nap schedules, and safe sleep habits.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How much sleep does a 6–9 month old need?',
    answer: 'Most babies this age need 12–15 hours of total sleep in a 24-hour period. This typically includes a longer stretch of 10–12 hours at night and 2–3 daytime naps totaling 2–4 hours. Every baby is different, but the American Academy of Sleep Medicine (AASM) recommends these totals for optimal health.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is there a 6-month or 8-month sleep regression?',
    answer: 'Yes. Many parents notice regressions around 6 months (often due to hitting milestones like rolling or sitting) and again around 8–9 months (due to crawling, pulling to stand, and separation anxiety). These "regressions" are actually signs of significant brain development and typically resolve within 1–2 weeks if you maintain consistent routines.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can my 6–9 month old sleep through the night without a feeding?',
    answer: 'By 6 months, many healthy, full-term babies are physically capable of sleeping 6–8 hours (or longer) without a night feeding. However, some babies still need one feeding during the night until closer to 9–12 months. Always consult your pediatrician before weaning night feedings to ensure your baby is meeting growth targets.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When do babies drop to two naps?',
    answer: 'Most babies transition from three naps to two between 6 and 9 months. Signs your baby is ready include resisting the third nap, shorter naps than usual, or suddenly having trouble falling asleep at bedtime. The morning and afternoon naps usually lengthen as the "catnap" disappears.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is it safe to have a blanket in the crib at 9 months?',
    answer: 'No. The AAP recommends keeping the sleep environment free of blankets, pillows, bumpers, and soft toys until at least 12 months of age to reduce the risk of SIDS and suffocation. A wearable blanket (sleep sack) is a safe alternative to keep your baby warm.',
  },
];

const aSchema = articleSchema({
  title,
  description,
  url: 'https://ageexpectations.com/ages/6-9-months/sleep/',
});
const fSchema = faqSchema(faqs);
---
<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  articleSchema={aSchema}
  faqSchema={fSchema}
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: '6–9 Months', href: '/ages/6-9-months/' },
    { label: 'Sleep' },
  ]}
>
  <h1>6–9 Month Old Sleep: What to Expect and Is It Normal?</h1>

  <p>The 6-to-9-month window is often a period of "sleep peaks and valleys." On one hand, many babies are finally capable of longer stretches of nighttime sleep and have established a more predictable nap routine. On the other hand, a literal explosion of physical milestones—crawling, sitting up, and pulling to stand—can make "staying asleep" a challenge for their busy brains.</p>

  <p>Understanding these developmental shifts can help you navigate the late-night wakeups and nap transitions with more confidence and less frustration.</p>

  <h2>Typical 6–9 Month Sleep Patterns</h2>
  <p>According to the AAP and the American Academy of Sleep Medicine, infants in this age range typically exhibit the following sleep behaviors:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Total Sleep:</strong> 12 to 15 hours per 24-hour period.</li>
    <li><strong>Night Sleep:</strong> 10 to 12 hours, often with one or no feedings for healthy babies.</li>
    <li><strong>Naps:</strong> Transitioning from 3 naps down to 2 naps by the 9-month mark.</li>
    <li><strong>Wake Windows:</strong> Most babies can comfortably stay awake for 2.5 to 3.5 hours between sleep periods.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Impact of Physical Milestones</h2>
  <p>At this age, your baby isn't just growing; they are "practicing." It is very common for a 7-month-old to wake up in the middle of the night and immediately pop into a sitting position or try to crawl across the crib. Because these skills are new, they often don't know how to "get back down" to a sleeping position, leading to cries for help.</p>
  <p><strong>Tip:</strong> Practice "falling down" or moving from sitting to lying down during floor time during the day. This helps them master the motor planning needed to settle themselves back to sleep at night.</p>

  <h2>Separation Anxiety and Sleep</h2>
  <p>Around 8 or 9 months, babies begin to understand "object permanence"—the idea that you still exist even when you aren't in the room. This awareness, while a great cognitive milestone, often triggers separation anxiety. Your baby may cry the moment you leave the room at bedtime or when they wake up and realize you aren't there. This is a normal phase and a sign of a healthy attachment.</p>

  <h2>Establishing a Consistent Routine</h2>
  <p>As your baby becomes more aware of the world, a consistent bedtime routine becomes even more important. A predictable sequence of events—such as bath, pajamas, a short story or song, and then into the crib—signals to the brain that it is time to transition to sleep. The AAP recommends that babies be placed in their crib while "drowsy but awake" to help them learn the vital skill of falling asleep independently.</p>

  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Is This Normal? Common Questions About 6–9 Month Sleep</h2>
    {faqs.map(faq => (
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-question">{faq.question}</p>
        <p class="faq-answer">{faq.answer}</p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <h2>Safe Sleep Reminders</h2>
    <p>Even as your baby becomes more mobile, safe sleep practices remain critical. Per AAP guidelines:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Always place your baby on their back to sleep.</li>
      <li>Use a firm, flat sleep surface (a crib or bassinet mattress).</li>
      <li>Keep the crib empty—no blankets, pillows, bumpers, or toys.</li>
      <li>Room-share (but do not bed-share) for at least the first 6 months, and ideally the first year.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
